{{Infobox religious building|religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]]|religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]]|religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]]| religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] | name = Nagasaki Toshogu Shrine | image = File:NagasakiToshogu.jpg|250px | location = {{ill|Nagasaki City, Nagasaki Prefecture|ja|長崎市|lt=Nagasaki City|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nagasaki Prefecture|ja|長崎県|lt=Nagasaki Prefecture|12=draft|12=draft}}, Kamiyamayacho 19 | iso = JP-42 | latitude_deg = | latitude_min = | latitude_sec = | longitude_deg = | longitude_min = | longitude_sec = | label_position = left | kami = | shrine_Rank = | founded = 1672 (Kanbun 12) | main_hall = {{ill|Irimoya-zukuri|ja|入母屋造|lt=Irimoya-zukuri|12=draft|12=draft}} | alias = | pilgrimage_site = | festival = | ceremonies = | map = }}
'''Nagasaki Toshogu Shrine''' (ながさきとうしょうぐう, Nagasaki Toshogu-gū<ref group=annotation>The official name is "Toshogu Shrine," and "Nagasaki Toshogu Shrine" is its common name.</ref>) is a {{ill|Toshogu Shrine|ja|東照宮|lt=Toshogu Shrine|12=draft|12=draft}} enshrined in {{ill|Nagasaki City|ja|長崎市|lt=Nagasaki City|12=draft|12=draft}}.
Its enshrinement site is in {{ill|Kamiyamayacho|ja|上西山町|lt=Kamiyamayacho|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nagasaki City|ja|長崎市|lt=Nagasaki City|12=draft|12=draft}}. The shrine building is built in a {{ill|Irimoya-zukuri|ja|入母屋造|lt=Irimoya-zukuri|12=draft|12=draft}} style with three ken and one go (traditional Japanese architectural units), and features a stone torii gate at the front. In one corner of the precincts, the {{ill|Nagasaki Prefecture Shinto Association building|ja|長崎県神社庁舎|lt=Nagasaki Prefecture Shinto Association building|12=draft|12=draft}} has been constructed.<ref name=NagasakiToshogu>Harutoshi Takato, "Ieyasu and All Toshogu Shrines Nationwide" Tokyo Bijutsu, pp. 133, 233.</ref>
At {{ill|Chinsei Taisha Suwa Jinja|ja|鎮西大社諏訪神社|lt=Chinsei Taisha Suwa Jinja|12=draft|12=draft}}, a ritual of drawing young water from the precinct's well and offering it to Toshogu Shrine was performed annually every New Year starting from the {{ill|Hōreki era|ja|宝暦|lt=Hōreki era|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name=NagasakiToshogu/>
== History == In {{ill|Kanbun era|ja|寛文|lt=Kanbun era|12=draft|12=draft}} 12 (1672), {{ill|Sakaue Tamuramaro|ja|坂上田村麻呂|lt=Sakaue Tamuramaro|12=draft|12=draft}} founded the shrine on the night of January 16 at midnight, along with {{ill|Anzen-ji|ja|安禅寺|lt=Anzen-ji|12=draft|12=draft}} (which was abolished during the {{ill|Haibutsu kishaku|ja|廃仏毀釈|lt=Haibutsu kishaku|12=draft|12=draft}}). It was named {{ill|Jigan-ji|ja|慈眼寺|lt=Jigan-ji|12=draft|12=draft}} as a branch temple (別当寺) of the {{ill|Suwa Taisha|ja|諏訪大社|lt=Suwa Taisha|12=draft|12=draft}} Upper Shrine.
During the {{ill|Kōnin era|ja|弘仁|lt=Kōnin era|12=draft|12=draft}}, under the guidance of {{ill|Kūkai|ja|空海|lt=Kūkai|12=draft|12=draft}} (Kōbō Daishi), {{ill|Shinjūji|ja|神宮寺|lt=Shinjūji|12=draft|12=draft}} became a temple for spreading {{ill|Shingon Buddhism|ja|真言宗|lt=Shingon Buddhism|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Jigan-ji|ja|慈眼寺|lt=Jigan-ji|12=draft|12=draft}} served as an educational dojo for Shingon Buddhism, designated as a {{ill|Jōhō Tanrinsho|ja|常法談林所|lt=Jōhō Tanrinsho|12=draft|12=draft}}, and was hailed as "the foremost dojo among the four temple schools in Shinshu."
In {{ill|Bunwa era|ja|文和|lt=Bunwa era|12=draft|12=draft}} 1 (1352), under Master {{ill|Shun-Kai Hōshi|ja|俊海法師|lt=Shun-Kai Hōshi|12=draft|12=draft}}, the temple site was relocated. In {{ill|Eiroku era|ja|永禄|lt=Eiroku era|12=draft|12=draft}} 3 (1560), during Master {{ill|Soncho Hōshi|ja|尊朝法師|lt=Soncho Hōshi|12=draft|12=draft}}, it moved to its current location and was renamed "Buppou Shoryuji." During the Edo period, it became a prayer temple for the {{ill|Suwa Domain|ja|諏訪藩|lt=Suwa Domain|12=draft|12=draft}}. In the Taishō period, it encountered a great fire, destroying the main hall, kitchen, founding hall, Kongōden, and corridors, but the main hall, kitchen, and founding hall were rebuilt. In Heisei 1 (1889), {{ill|Chieidō|ja|智映堂|lt=Chieidō|12=draft|12=draft}} was established.
Subsequently, the Toshogu Shrine was revered by successive {{ill|Nagasaki Magistrates|ja|長崎奉行|lt=Nagasaki Magistrates|12=draft|12=draft}} and commoners. During the end of the Edo period, {{ill|Katsu Kaishū|ja|勝海舟|lt=Katsu Kaishū|12=draft|12=draft}}, who visited the shrine, donated a wakizashi sword.<ref>Harutoshi Takato, "Ieyasu and All Toshogu Shrines Nationwide" Tokyo Bijutsu, p. 132.</ref>
The priests of the branch temple of Toshogu Shrine received the same treatment as the local officials of Nagasaki, being allocated ceremonial silver (地役人の給与。貿易利益や、貿易関係の諸税から配分された。)<ref group=annotation>Essentially, this refers to the salaries of local officials, distributed from trade profits and various trade-related taxes.</ref>.<ref>Maiko Tomori, "Retainers of the Edo Shogunate" Tokyo Do Publishing, p. 340.</ref>
After {{ill|Anzen-ji|ja|安禅寺|lt=Anzen-ji|12=draft|12=draft}} was abolished in {{ill|Meiji era|ja|明治|lt=Meiji era|12=draft|12=draft}} 1, the shrine lost its managing priest and the shrine building fell into disrepair, so it was temporarily enshrined together with {{ill|Suwa Jinja|ja|諏訪神社|lt=Suwa Jinja|12=draft|12=draft}}. In {{ill|Meiji era|ja|明治|lt=Meiji era|12=draft|12=draft}} 30 (1897), the shrine building was rebuilt, and {{ill|Tadayoshi Takagi|ja|高木忠悦|lt=Tadayoshi Takagi|12=draft|12=draft}}, a local official in Nagasaki, was appointed as the managing priest. In {{ill|Meiji era|ja|明治|lt=Meiji era|12=draft|12=draft}} 43 (1910), the Nagasaki General Town Assembly was held, and it was decided that the shrine would become {{ill|Toshogu Jinja|ja|東照宮神社|lt=Toshogu Jinja|12=draft|12=draft}} and become a branch shrine of {{ill|Suwa Jinja|ja|諏訪神社|lt=Suwa Jinja|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name=Anzen-ji/><ref>Harutoshi Takato, "Ieyasu and All Toshogu Shrines Nationwide" Tokyo Bijutsu, pp. 132-133.</ref>
