== History == In {{ill|Kanbun era|ja|寛文|lt=Kanbun era|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanbun era|qq=}} 12 (1672), {{ill|Sakaue Tamuramaro|ja|坂上田村麻呂|lt=Sakaue Tamuramaro|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakaue Tamuramaro|qq=}} founded the shrine on the night of January 16 at midnight, along with {{ill|Anzen-ji|ja|安禅寺|lt=Anzen-ji|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Anzen-ji|qq=}} (which was abolished during the {{ill|Haibutsu kishaku|ja|廃仏毀釈|1=Haibutsu kishaku|lt=Haibutsu kishaku|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Haibutsu kishaku|13=User:Immanuelle/Haibutsu kishaku|qq=}}). It was named {{ill|Jigan-ji|ja|慈眼寺|lt=Jigan-ji|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jigan-ji|qq=}} as a branch temple (別当寺) of the {{ill|Suwa Taisha|ja|諏訪大社|lt=Suwa Taisha|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Taisha|qq=}} Upper Shrine.
During the {{ill|Kōnin era|ja|弘仁|lt=Kōnin era|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōnin era|qq=}}, under the guidance of {{ill|Kūkai|ja|空海|lt=Kūkai|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kūkai|qq=}} (Kōbō Daishi), {{ill|Shinjūji|ja|神宮寺|lt=Shinjūji|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinjūji|qq=}} became a temple for spreading {{ill|Shingon Buddhism|ja|真言宗|lt=Shingon Buddhism|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shingon Buddhism|qq=}} and {{ill|Jigan-ji|ja|慈眼寺|lt=Jigan-ji|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jigan-ji|qq=}} served as an educational dojo for Shingon Buddhism, designated as a {{ill|Jōhō Tanrinsho|ja|常法談林所|lt=Jōhō Tanrinsho|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōhō Tanrinsho|qq=}}, and was hailed as "the foremost dojo among the four temple schools in Shinshu."
In {{ill|Bunwa era|ja|文和|lt=Bunwa era|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bunwa era|qq=}} 1 (1352), under Master {{ill|Shun-Kai Hōshi|ja|俊海法師|lt=Shun-Kai Hōshi|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shun-Kai Hōshi|qq=}}, the temple site was relocated. In {{ill|Eiroku era|ja|永禄|lt=Eiroku era|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Eiroku era|qq=}} 3 (1560), during Master {{ill|Soncho Hōshi|ja|尊朝法師|lt=Soncho Hōshi|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Soncho Hōshi|qq=}}, it moved to its current location and was renamed "Buppou Shoryuji." During the Edo period, it became a prayer temple for the {{ill|Suwa Domain|ja|諏訪藩|lt=Suwa Domain|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Domain|qq=}}. In the Taishō period, it encountered a great fire, destroying the main hall, kitchen, founding hall, Kongōden, and corridors, but the main hall, kitchen, and founding hall were rebuilt. In Heisei 1 (1889), {{ill|Chieidō|ja|智映堂|lt=Chieidō|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chieidō|qq=}} was established.
Subsequently, the Toshogu Shrine was revered by successive {{ill|Nagasaki Magistrates|ja|長崎奉行|lt=Nagasaki Magistrates|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nagasaki Magistrates|qq=}} and commoners. During the end of the Edo period, {{ill|Katsu Kaishū|ja|勝海舟|lt=Katsu Kaishū|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Katsu Kaishū|qq=}}, who visited the shrine, donated a wakizashi sword.<ref>Harutoshi Takato, "Ieyasu and All Toshogu Shrines Nationwide" Tokyo Bijutsu, p. 132.</ref>
The priests of the branch temple of Toshogu Shrine received the same treatment as the local officials of Nagasaki, being allocated ceremonial silver (地役人の給与。貿易利益や、貿易関係の諸税から配分された。)<ref group=annotation>Essentially, this refers to the salaries of local officials, distributed from trade profits and various trade-related taxes.</ref>.<ref>Maiko Tomori, "Retainers of the Edo Shogunate" Tokyo Do Publishing, p. 340.</ref>
After {{ill|Anzen-ji|ja|安禅寺|lt=Anzen-ji|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Anzen-ji|qq=}} was abolished in {{ill|Meiji era|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|lt=Meiji era|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|qq=}} 1, the shrine lost its managing priest and the shrine building fell into disrepair, so it was temporarily enshrined together with {{ill|Suwa Jinja|ja|諏訪神社|lt=Suwa Jinja|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Jinja|qq=}}. In {{ill|Meiji era|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|lt=Meiji era|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|qq=}} 30 (1897), the shrine building was rebuilt, and {{ill|Tadayoshi Takagi|ja|高木忠悦|lt=Tadayoshi Takagi|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tadayoshi Takagi|qq=}}, a local official in Nagasaki, was appointed as the managing priest. In {{ill|Meiji era|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|lt=Meiji era|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|qq=}} 43 (1910), the Nagasaki General Town Assembly was held, and it was decided that the shrine would become {{ill|Toshogu Jinja|ja|東照宮神社|lt=Toshogu Jinja|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toshogu Jinja|qq=}} and become a branch shrine of {{ill|Suwa Jinja|ja|諏訪神社|lt=Suwa Jinja|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Jinja|qq=}}.<ref name=Anzen-ji/><ref>Harutoshi Takato, "Ieyasu and All Toshogu Shrines Nationwide" Tokyo Bijutsu, pp. 132-133.</ref>
